## LOCKED DECISIONS

1. **Brand name is always lowercase.** `inboxrow`, never capitalised. Labels
   use `text-transform: uppercase`, so anywhere the name sits inside one it
   opts out with `normal-case` (footer copyright, comparison-table headers,
   the cost panel label). Enforced across copy, `<title>`, and meta.

2. **Palette, byte-identical.** `#FF4835` red ¬∑ `#35ABFF` blue ¬∑ `#FCFCFC`
   white ¬∑ `#101014` black. Roles are **inherited from the product app's**
   `src/app/tokens.css` so a visitor who becomes a user never relearns what a
   colour means:
   - **Blue is the interface accent** ‚Äî primary CTA, focus ring, state, links.
   - **Red is the wordmark, the single hero moment, and danger only.** In the
     app, `--signal` red encodes "exited the funnel" / "danger", so spending
     it on ordinary accents would make the marketing site read as errors. It
     appears in exactly two places: the wordmark, and the highlight behind
     "row" in the hero.

3. **Inter only.** Loaded from rsms.me, `InterVariable` behind an
   `@supports (font-variation-settings: normal)` check. No monospace, no
   second family. The technical feel of `.tag` labels comes from 0.06em
   tracking + uppercase, not a second typeface.

4. **Two font weights, each with one job.** `400` running text, `600`
   headings / UI labels / emphasis. Inter Variable will happily render 540 or
   590 ‚Äî an earlier pass had SEVEN weights in use, which is how a page stops
   looking decided. Do not reintroduce a third.

5. **One canvas colour.** Every section is `#FCFCFC`. No section is separated
   by a background change ‚Äî structure comes from hairline rules, a continuous
   framed column (`max-w-[1280px]`, `border-x`), and a sticky label rail. The
   only contrast moment on the page is the ink request-access panel.

6. **The row is the design atom.** Tagline is "earn a row in the inbox," so
   inbox rows, mailbox counts, volume bars, steps, audiences and FAQ entries
   are all the same horizontal element at different scales. The product app
   independently owns this metaphor (`RowMeter`, `RowBreakdown`,
   `funnelFromStatuses`, a `--funnel-*` scale).

7. **No em dashes or en dashes anywhere.** The source markdown leaned on them
   heavily; each was rewritten into a real sentence, comma or colon rather
   than swapped for another glyph. Apostrophes are curly (`‚Äô`). Keep this in
   mind when editing `src/content/site.ts`.

8. **Copy rules from the brief.** Every CTA is *Request access* (invite-only,
   never "Sign up"). **No open/click/reply stats anywhere** ‚Äî bot-inflated.
   Volume and cost numbers ARE the pitch. **Never imply warm-up can be
   skipped**; the differentiator is volume per warmed mailbox.

9. **No Google/Workspace/Gmail references in copy (July 2026).** The pitch was
   genericized to "your own email / your own mailboxes"; limits are phrased as
   "your provider's limit". Enforced across `site.ts`, `index.html` meta, and
   the inline strings in `cost.tsx` / `volume.tsx`. Don't reintroduce the
   provider name when editing copy (the product app is still Gmail-based;
   that's internal, not a marketing claim).

